      "proposed_solution": null,
      "question": "<p>We have identified a continuous flow of water discharging into the pond from the existing 60-inch outfall located beneath the roadway at approximately STA 28+50. The current elevation of the outfall discharge is approximately EL. 7.0, while the inflow elevation of the 60-inch pipe is approximately EL. 8.5.</p>\n<p>At this time, there are no proposed grading details that adequately capture or convey this discharge away from the pond. This condition will present a conflict with the proposed berm installation and may impact overall site performance.</p>\n<p>For reference, the existing roof drain outfalls along the north edge of the site (feeding from beneath the warehouse) are as follows:</p>\n<p>STA 34+00 – EL. 4.61<br>STA 36+50 – EL. 4.85<br>STA 37+00 – EL. 4.80<br>STA 38+25 – EL. 5.11<br>STA 39+25 – EL. 5.01<br>STA 40+50 – EL. 5.70</p>\n<p>Please advise on how you would like to address the discharge from the 60-inch outfall, including any required grading revisions or stormwater management measures to properly convey flow and avoid conflicts with the berm.</p>\n<p>In the interim, and for temporary construction purposes, Myers proposes to cut channels to divert the flow away from the work area into the pond and continue pumping out the pond. This approach is intended to manage flow and prevent impacts to undercutting and backfill operations.</p>",
      "question_created_at": "2026-04-01T14:55:52.097108+00:00",
      "received_from": "Smith Joe (Allan Myers)",
