      "proposed_solution": null,
      "question": "<p>Please clarify the below discrepancies shown in the Contract Plans: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>1. The storm Manholes are shown on plan sheet “273-0010” as 60” Dia. And 72” Dia. Manholes per the Storm Structure <br>Table and were bid as shown and provided by the Engineer.  Upon further analysis while running elevation sheets, these <br>Manholes cannot be precast in the diameters shown due to the OD (Outside Dia.) of the 48”, 60” and existing RCP.   </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>60” RCP has an OD of 72” and needs a rough opening of 78”.  Due to the size, number and orientation of pipes, the Storm <br>Manholes cannot be constructed as shown on the plans.  Some of the 72” Dia would need to be increased up to 120” <br>which greatly increases material, transport and installation costs.  Myers will be requesting additional compensation due <br>to this change.  As discussed at Pre-Con, Myers is proposing an alternate pipe material to reduce manhole sizes and <br>provide a value engineer savings to Tradepoint (TPA).  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>If option 3 below is acceptable, all (or most) of the Manholes can be constructed at 84” or 96” Dia reducing additional <br>cost.   <br>Rough order of magnitude cost to increase manholes from 72” to 84”/96” is $2,000 EA. <br>Rough order of magnitude cost to increase manholes from 72” to 120” is $11,000 EA. <br>*material only </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>2. Many of the Manholes are too shallow to meet the Rim (top of structure) elevation noted in the plans. Is it acceptable to <br>proceed with Rim elevations above finish grade?  These structures would stick up slightly (approx.. 12” +/-) and Myers <br>could grade around them to blend. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>If option 3 below is acceptable, the severity and quantity of shallow conflicts is minimized or eliminated.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>3. In an effort to minimize the above impact in items 1 &amp; 2 of drastically increasing the Manhole sizes and varying grades, <br>would the Engineer accept using an alternate pipe material for the storm drain?  Either HDPE ADS N-12 per ASTM F2648 <br>or HDPE HP Storm?  See attached specification sheets and material properties; the HDPE HP Storm is considered an <br>industry equivalent to RCP.  The flow diameter would remain the same as original design, however the OD of these pipes <br>will decrease and allow for additional space in Manhole construction and grade clearance.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>As a rough order of magnitude, if acceptable to the Engineer and TPA, Myers can offer credit in the tune of: </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>-$203k if HP Storm is acceptable. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>-$390k if N-12 is acceptable.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>See below charts and other data with rough order of magnitude values in the pdf attachment.   </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>*above values are approximate shown for conceptual purposes only to be finalized with backup upon approval.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>If acceptable, please advise which pipe alternate and Myers will submit a formalized proposal to finalize the credit offer <br>and move forward with Manhole pricing, shop drawings/submittals.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>4. What is the intention of the note on sheet “251-006” for MH-108 that calls for Storm Drainage Manhole With Inlet <br>(Typ.)?  Does this just require a perforated manhole cover to allow for drainage or does the detail on sheet “260-0003” <br>NJ Standards apply?  Why would there be a curb inlet in this location?  There is no bid item for Inlet Style Drainage <br>Structure as this note was not included in the 90% bid set.  </p>\n<p> </p>",
      "question_created_at": "2026-02-25T04:47:33.968993+00:00",
