      "question": "<p>During installation of the proposed storm drain at approximately STA. 45+60, Allan Myers encountered a conflict with the existing 60\" waterline.</p>\n<p>Based on current field observations, the invert elevation of the proposed storm pipe at approximately 230 LF upstream of MH-100 is Elev. (0.82). The top of the existing 60\" waterline at the conflict location was found to be Elev. (3.09), which creates an interference with the proposed storm drain alignment.</p>\n<p>Myers previously test-pitted the existing 60\" waterline approximately 10 feet from this location and found the top of pipe elevation to be Elev. (-1.56). Based on these findings, Myers assumes the existing waterline transitions upward in front of the proposed storm drain via a bend and kicker, then bends again to return to a deeper elevation.</p>\n<p>As a potential solution to avoid the conflict and maintain the proposed storm drain alignment to MH-101, Myers proposes revising the run to include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>One (1) 45-degree bend</li>\n<li>A section of straight pipe</li>\n<li>One (1) additional 45-degree bend</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This adjustment would allow the proposed storm drain to bypass the existing waterline and tie back into the intended alignment at MH-101.</p>\n<p>Please refer to the attached plan markup for reference and advise how Myers should proceed.</p>",
      "question_created_at": "2026-04-17T13:46:30.351642+00:00",
